                    <span>most books basically teach you how c++ is different from c, which distorts the perspective.
<br />
<br />e.g. examples typically include creating a string class. as if c++ hasn't had one of those for a decade.
<br />
<br />this book is the only one i have found that approaches c++ (and its libraries) as a language in its own right.
<br />
<br />this approach allows the author to correctly prioritize the material, which ultimately will make you a more efficient and accomplished programmer.
<br />
<br />this is the only book i would recommend to beginners.</span>
                  
              
